description.value: Vessel made of calcite in a very eroded state that was used as a kohl pot. Most parts of the rim are broken off. The interior is hollowed out comparatively deep and with straight sides. The base is flat and the vessel is tapered to the base while the shoulders are quite wide. At the exterior as well as interior salt accretions on the surface.

description.value: Flat base or lid of a vessel made of calcite with a diameter of 11 cm. The exterior surface of the base itself is so well smoothed that it suggests a primary usage as a lid. The exterior walls were at least 4.5 cm high. The object was later reused as a bowl. At that stage the exterior walls that were broken off were preserved at slightly different heights and were smoothed irrespective of the varying heights. The interior surface of the bowl shows a circular depression of a diameter of 5 cm that is slightly acentric. This suggests a usage as a mortar.

description.value: Part of the base of a vessel made of calcite. The base is very thick walled and heavy, suggesting a closed shape but the highly polished surface of the interior suggests an open shape like a bowl. The rim is broken off and the side walls are very thin compared to the base. The shape of the vessel is tapered towards the base. The surface of the base is less well smoothed than the outer and inner interior.

description.value: 'Kohl' tube of palm-column form: the opaque lavender-blue shaft has a glossy surface, its lower half decorated with slender chevrons of white and yellow glass. The elements of the capital are outlined with yellow  threads while a white thread encircles the   opening. Assembled from two pieces through centre of body.   A turquoise-blue glass applicator of conventional form not separately numbered accompanies this tube.
